SIMPLE: precept
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Precept
<hw>Pre"cept</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>praeceptum</ets>, from <ets>praecipere</ets> to take beforehand, to
instruct, teach; <ets>prae</ets> before + <ets>capere</ets> to take: cf.
F. <ets>pr⟦eacute⟧cepte</ets>. See <er>Pre-</er>, and
<er>Capacious</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Any commandment,
instruction, or order intended as an authoritative rule of action; esp.,
a command respecting moral conduct; an injunction; a rule.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For <qex>precept</qex> must be upon <qex>precept</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Isa. xxviii. 10.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No arts are without their <qex>precepts</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>A command in writing; a species of
writ or process.</def> <rj><au>Burrill.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Commandment; injunction; mandate; law; rule;
direction; principle; maxim. See <er>Doctrine</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Precept</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Precept
<hw>Pre"cept</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To teach by precepts.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Preceptial</ent>⟦br⟧
